<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-03T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-03T23:00:00-05:00" n="45" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d45">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.801 Search/9: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-04T12:00:00+08:00">March 4,
                                1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 4—5:30
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>169. Legation’s 166, March 3, 1 p.m. Following from Hankow: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“March 3, 3 p.m. My February 27, noon. General Ho Chien has now
                                    replied stating that the search is for the purpose of
                                    suppressing movements of Communists. This statement does not
                                    harmonize with statements made by the soldiers themselves who
                                    assert that it is for the purpose of enforcing embargo against
                                    shipment of rice out of Hunan.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>